## Animation

```css
:root {
  --ease-out: cubic-bezier(0.25, 0.46, 0.45, 0.94);
  --ease-spring: cubic-bezier(0.34, 1.56, 0.64, 1);
  --ease-smooth: cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
  --duration-fast: 150ms;
  --duration-normal: 250ms;
  --duration-slow: 400ms;
}
```

Every state change gets a transition. No interaction without visual feedback. Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.

---

## Interaction Patterns

- **Keyboard shortcuts**: Every primary action needs one. Show hints in `<kbd>` badges next to actions.
- **Command Palette** (`Cmd+K`): centered floating modal with backdrop blur for multi-section search.
- **Drag and drop**: highlight drop zones with dashed accent border + subtle accent background.
- **Optimistic UI**: show result immediately, process async, revert on failure.
- **Progressive disclosure**: hide filters/toolbars until content exists. Advanced options behind "..." menus.
- **Empty states**: centered icon + one line of text + CTA. Hide all secondary UI.

---

## Borders

Use borders sparingly. macOS uses very thin (0.5px), low-opacity borders. Never thick or dark borders. Hierarchy comes from background shade differences, not borders.

---

## Anti-Patterns (NEVER do these)

- Pure black (#000000) backgrounds — Apple uses dark grays (#1C1C1E)
- Pure white (#FFFFFF) text on dark — use #F5F5F7
- Thick, visible borders for separation — use background shade differences
- Heavy drop shadows — use layered, subtle multi-shadow
- Custom/Google fonts for UI text — system fonts only
- Accent color on large background areas — highlights and interactive elements only
- Directly inverting light mode colors for dark mode
- Cluttered top bar / toolbar — keep it sparse, let it breathe
